@prefix :       <#> .
@prefix schema: <http://schema.org/> .
@prefix rdfs:   <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
@prefix xsd:    <http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#> .
@prefix onto:   <https://www.openlinksw.com/ontology/> .

# ── Self-describing document entity ──────────────────────────────────────────

<> a schema:CreativeWork ;
    schema:name "HowTo: KG Curation Attribution Pattern"@en ;
    schema:description "Companion howto for preferences.ttl Step 47. Specifies the pattern for crediting knowledge graph curation in hero-meta lines and infographic headers: skills + AI agent acting on behalf of the human principal."@en ;
    schema:dateCreated "2026-06-14T00:00:00Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:dateModified "2026-07-05T00:00:00Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:about :HowToKgCurationAttribution .

# ── HowTo ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

:HowToKgCurationAttribution a schema:HowTo ;
    schema:name "KG Curation Attribution — Skills, AI Agent, and Human Principal"@en ;
    schema:description "When displaying a curation credit in a knowledge graph infographic, expose the full provenance chain: which skills were used, which AI agent executed them, and on whose behalf. Never collapse this to a bare human name."@en ;
    schema:step :stepPattern,
                :stepHtmlMarkup,
                :stepSubstitutionRules,
                :stepAntiPatterns,
                :stepRdfDelegation,
                :stepEntityLevelAuthorship .

# ── Steps ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

:stepPattern a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position 1 ;
    schema:name "Core pattern"@en ;
    schema:text """KG curated by {relevant-skills} and {relevant-ai-agent} on behalf of [Kingsley Idehen]({resolver-IRI})

Where:
  {relevant-skills}    = the skill(s) that produced the KG (e.g., kg-generator, rdf-infographic-skill)
  {relevant-ai-agent}  = the LLM/model that executed the skills (e.g., Claude Sonnet 4.6)
  {resolver-IRI}       = the URIBurner resolver URL for Kingsley's LinkedIn IRI (see stepSubstitutionRules)

This makes the provenance chain machine-readable and human-readable:
  Skills → AI agent → Human principal"""@en .

:stepHtmlMarkup a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position 2 ;
    schema:name "HTML markup template"@en ;
    schema:text """Place in the .hero-meta <p> element, delimited by &nbsp;·&nbsp;:

  &nbsp;·&nbsp; KG curated by
  <a href="https://github.com/OpenLinkSoftware/ai-agent-skills/tree/main/kg-generator"
     target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">kg-generator</a>,
  <a href="https://github.com/OpenLinkSoftware/ai-agent-skills/tree/main/rdf-infographic-skill"
     target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">rdf-infographic-skill</a>,
  and <a href="{llm-canonical-url}"
     target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">{llm-name}</a>
  on behalf of
  <a href="https://linkeddata.uriburner.com/describe/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fin%2Fkidehen%23this"
     target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Kingsley Idehen</a>

All links inherit color from .hero-meta a { color: var(--accent); text-decoration: none; }.
All links use target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"."""@en .

:stepSubstitutionRules a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position 3 ;
    schema:name "Substitution rules for template variables"@en ;
    schema:text """Skill URLs:
  Always use the canonical GitHub repo URL:
  https://github.com/OpenLinkSoftware/ai-agent-skills/tree/main/{skill-name}
  Never use the #this IRI suffix in the href — that is for JSON-LD prov:wasGeneratedBy only.

LLM URL:
  Use the model's canonical product page (verbatim from existing footer, never fabricated).
  Claude Sonnet 4.6 → https://www.anthropic.com/claude

Kingsley Idehen resolver IRI:
  https://linkeddata.uriburner.com/describe/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fin%2Fkidehen%23this
  This is the URIBurner resolver pattern applied to the canonical LinkedIn IRI
  (https://www.linkedin.com/in/kidehen#this). Do not shorten or alter the percent-encoding.

Skill list grammar:
  - One skill:  "KG curated by {skill} and {llm} on behalf of …"
  - Two skills: "KG curated by {skill1}, {skill2}, and {llm} on behalf of …"
  - N skills:   Oxford-comma list ending with "and {llm}"
  The LLM is always the final item before "on behalf of" — it is not a skill."""@en .

:stepRdfDelegation a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position 5 ;
    schema:name "Encode delegation in embedded JSON-LD using PROV-O and schema.org"@en ;
    schema:text """When the HTML infographic contains a <script type="application/ld+json"> block, encode the delegation relationship using three complementary vocabulary layers:

1. On the WebPage/CreativeWork entity (document level):
   "accountablePerson": { "@id": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/kidehen#this" }
   These express: (schema.org) who is accountable for the content; complements
   the existing "author" field which already points to the same WebID.
   Use schema:author (already required) — do NOT add foaf:maker.

2. On each generating agent in prov:wasGeneratedBy:
   - Add "@type": ["SoftwareApplication", "prov:SoftwareAgent"]
   - Add "prov:actedOnBehalfOf": { "@id": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/kidehen#this" }
   This expresses: this software agent executed under delegation from Kingsley's WebID.

The two layers are semantically complementary:
  schema:author                              = document authorship (WebID of principal)
  schema:accountablePerson                   = schema.org accountability term (same WebID)
  prov:wasGeneratedBy + prov:actedOnBehalfOf = provenance chain (tool → principal)

Kingsley's WebID IRI: https://www.linkedin.com/in/kidehen#this
(Do not use the resolver URL here — the @id must be the canonical WebID IRI, not the describe/?url= form.)"""@en .

:stepAntiPatterns a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position 4 ;
    schema:name "Anti-patterns — what NOT to do"@en ;
    schema:text """❌ "KG curated by Kingsley Idehen"
   → Missing: skill provenance, AI agent; human name is bare text, not resolver-linked.

❌ "KG curated by Claude on behalf of Kingsley Idehen"
   → Missing: skill attribution; LLM name is bare text, not hyperlinked.

❌ "Created by kg-generator and rdf-infographic-skill"
   → Missing: AI agent and human principal; phrase "created by" loses the delegation semantics.

❌ "KG curated by Kingsley Idehen using kg-generator"
   → Wrong order — human principal is the delegator, not the doer; skills and LLM are the agents.

✅ "KG curated by [kg-generator], [rdf-infographic-skill], and [Claude Sonnet 4.6] on behalf of [Kingsley Idehen]"
   where [] = hyperlinked to canonical URLs and resolver IRI respectively."""@en .

# ── Step 6: Entity-level authorship — the same delegation rule applies below the document level ──

:stepEntityLevelAuthorship a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position 6 ;
    schema:name "Never set schema:author of an agent-authored entity directly to the principal — apply the same delegation chain used at document level"@en ;
    schema:text """Found 2026-07-05: a generated collection modeled seven distinct 'Critical Perspective' entities distilling Kingsley Idehen's known public views, and set schema:author on each directly to Kingsley's WebID (<https://www.linkedin.com/in/kidehen#this>). This overclaims — the agent synthesized that specific text (informed by Kingsley's general public writing, not transcribed from a specific source document), it was not typed by Kingsley personally. Whoami semantics already establish the agent operates FOR/ON BEHALF OF the principal (:connection schema:additionalType "operates-for" in core.ttl) — that relationship must be reflected in authorship attribution on every entity the agent itself authors, not just at the top-level document/WebPage.

RULE: whenever the agent authors a specific sub-document entity (a critique, commentary, summary, or any distinct schema:CreativeWork/schema:Comment-typed node) that represents or is framed around the principal's views, apply the SAME three-layer delegation pattern used for whole-document curation credit (see stepRdfDelegation), at the ENTITY level:
  - schema:author           → the generating skill/agent entity (e.g. the kg-generator SoftwareAgent), NOT the principal's WebID directly
  - schema:accountablePerson → the principal's WebID (whose perspective/accountability this represents)
  - the skill/agent entity itself carries prov:actedOnBehalfOf → the principal's WebID (already required by stepRdfDelegation)

This distinguishes "I (the agent) wrote this distillation of your views, on your behalf" (correct) from "you personally wrote this text" (incorrect, and factually false when the agent synthesized rather than quoted). Visible prose (hero-meta, section intros, footer attribution) must use matching language: "curated by {skills+agent} on behalf of {principal}" or "the AI agent authored this on behalf of {principal}" — never a bare "by {principal}" or "authored by {principal}" for agent-synthesized content.

Anti-pattern: schema:author <principal-webid> on an entity the agent itself wrote. Correct pattern: schema:author <agent-entity> ; schema:accountablePerson <principal-webid> ."""@en .
